---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const accessibilityUtilities = `.vh {}
.a11y-link {}
.a11y-link--focusable {}`;

const vhExample = `.vh {
    position: absolute;
    inline-size: 1px;
    block-size: 1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    clip-path: inset(50%);
    white-space: nowrap;
}`;

const skipLinkExample = `.a11y-link {
    position: absolute;
    inset-block-start: 0;
    inset-inline-start: 0;
    transform: translateY(-100%);
}

.a11y-link--focusable:focus,
.a11y-link--focusable:focus-visible {
    transform: translateY(0);
}`;

const avoidExample = `<article class="p-4 mb-4 bg-white rounded shadow text-center grid gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Product title</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted mb-4">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const betterExample = `<article class="product-card">
    <h2 class="title">Product title</h2>
    <p class="description">Product description</p>
</article>`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Utilities"
    description="Utility classes in Layered Semantic CSS, including why most utilities should be avoided and where accessibility utilities are justified."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Utilities</p>

        <h1>
            Utility classes
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            In LSCSS, utility classes are rare exceptions. Most styling should
            live in semantic components, not in long chains of presentational
            classes in the HTML.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Utilities sections">
        <a href="#position">Position</a>
        <a href="#accessibility-utilities">Accessibility utilities</a>
        <a href="#when-to-use">When to use one</a>
        <a href="#avoid">Avoid</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="position" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Most utilities should not exist
        </h2>

        <p>
            LSCSS does not treat utility classes as a styling strategy. If a
            class exists mainly to push layout, spacing, typography, colour, or
            decoration into the HTML, it usually belongs in a component, theme,
            or layout partial instead.
        </p>

        <p>
            A utility should have to justify its existence. Accessibility
            helpers are the main exception because they solve universal browser
            and assistive technology problems rather than component-specific
            styling problems.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="accessibility-utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Accessibility utilities
        </h2>

        <p>
            These are the kind of utilities that fit LSCSS because they provide
            consistent accessibility behaviour across the whole project.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={accessibilityUtilities} />

        <h3>
            Visually hidden text
        </h3>

        <p>
            Use <code>.vh</code> for content that should be available to screen
            readers but visually hidden.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={vhExample} />

        <h3>
            Accessible jump links
        </h3>

        <p>
            Use <code>.a11y-link</code> with
            <code>.a11y-link--focusable</code> for skip links that become visible
            when focused.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={skipLinkExample} />
    </section>

    <section id="when-to-use" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            When a utility is justified
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>It solves a universal accessibility problem.</li>
            <li>It behaves consistently across the whole project.</li>
            <li>It does not replace a meaningful component class.</li>
            <li>It does not encourage long presentational class chains.</li>
            <li>It remains understandable without checking several other utilities.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            If the same group of styling utilities keeps appearing together, it
            is not a utility pattern. It is a component asking to be named.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="avoid" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Avoid class soup
        </h2>

        <p>
            Spacing, colour, typography, shadow, radius, and layout utilities can
            make HTML harder to scan and harder to refactor. They also spread
            design decisions across markup instead of keeping them in CSS.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={avoidExample} language="html" />

        <p>
            Prefer a semantic component when the HTML represents a real UI
            pattern.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={betterExample} language="html" />
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
